    {
      "title": "Definite and Indefinite Nouns (المعرفة والنكرة)",
      "titleArabic": "المعرفة والنكرة",
      "content": [
        "Arabic nouns are either definite (ma'rifa) or indefinite (nakira). Understanding this distinction is essential for proper agreement and usage in sentences."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Seven categories of definite nouns exist in Arabic",
        "Indefinite nouns take tanwīn (nunation)",
        "Vocative (nidā') can affect definiteness",
        "Proper nouns are inherently definite"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "الْكِتَابُ", "english": "the book (definite with al)" },
        { "arabic": "كِتَابٌ", "english": "a book (indefinite with tanwīn)" },
        { "arabic": "يَا مُحَمَّدُ", "english": "O Muhammad! (vocative)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Form VIII Verbs (اِفْتَعَلَ)",
      "titleArabic": "باب اِفْتَعَلَ",
      "content": [
        "Form VIII verbs are formed by prefixing اِ and inserting تَ after the first radical. This pattern can indicate reflexive action, effort, or mutual action."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Pattern: اِفْتَعَلَ (ifta'ala) - with infixed tā'",
        "Maṣdar pattern: اِفْتِعَال (ifti'āl)",
        "Assimilation rules apply when first radical is certain letters",
        "Can indicate effort or striving in an action"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "اِجْتَمَعَ", "english": "to gather / meet" },
        { "arabic": "اِسْتَمَعَ", "english": "to listen" },
        { "arabic": "اِخْتَارَ", "english": "to choose" }
      ]
    }
  ],
